Below is a self-contained ARC-style problem with three training examples and one test example, all in grids no larger than 10×10. The underlying “rule” (or analogy) is:

• Identify all objects of color 1 in the grid.  
• Shift each such object 2 cells to the right.  
• Recolor it to color 2.  
• Paint that recolored copy onto the original grid.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
EXPLANATION OF THE ANALOGY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Find all “objects” composed of contiguous cells of color 1.  
2. Shift each such object 2 cells to the right.  
3. Recolor the shifted copy to color 2.  
4. Paint the recolored copy on top of the original grid (overlaying overlaps).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SOLUTION (Hodel DSL PROGRAM)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Below is a possible “solve” function in terms of the provided DSL definitions. The main steps are:

• Extract all foreground objects from the grid (color 1 only).  
• Shift each object right by two columns.  
• Recolor it to 2.  
• Paint it back onto the grid.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
from arc_types import *

def solve(grid: Grid) -> Grid:
    # 1) Find all objects (univalued=True, diagonal=False, without_bg=True)
    all_objs = objects(grid, True, False, True)
    # 2) Filter to those whose color is 1
    objs_color1 = colorfilter(all_objs, 1)
    
    # We will start with a working copy of the original grid
    result = grid

    # 3) For each color-1 object, shift it right by 2 columns and recolor to 2
    for obj in objs_color1:
        obj_shifted = shift(obj, (0, 2))    # (0, +2) moves it right by 2
        obj_recolored = recolor(2, obj_shifted)
        # 4) Overlay/paint that recolored object onto our result
        result = paint(result, obj_recolored)
    
    return result

# The “solve” function, when called on each input grid of the training/test pairs,
# produces the corresponding output grid described in the ARC-like task above.
